##You may use the Laplace Approximation approach we used in lecture and the homework assignments.(Alternatively, you may use rstanarms stan_glm() function to fit full Bayesian linear models with syntax like Rs glm()).

logistic_logpost <- function(unknowns, my_info)
{
  # extract the design matrix and assign to X
  X <- my_info$design_matrix
  
  # calculate the linear predictor
  eta <- X %*% matrix(unknowns)
  
  # calculate the event probability
  mu <- boot::inv.logit(eta)
  
  # evaluate the log-likelihood
  log_lik <- sum(dbinom(x=my_info$yobs,
                        size=1,
                        prob=mu,
                        log=TRUE))
  
  # evaluate the log-prior
  log_prior <- sum(dnorm(x=unknowns,
                         mean=my_info$mu_beta,
                         sd=my_info$tau_beta,
                         log=TRUE))
  
  # sum together
  log_lik+log_prior
}
my_laplace <- function(start_guess, logpost_func, ...)
{
  # code adapted from the `LearnBayes`` function `laplace()`
  fit <- optim(start_guess,
               logpost_func,
               gr = NULL,
               ...,
               method = "BFGS",
               hessian = TRUE,
               control = list(fnscale = -1, maxit = 1001))
  
  mode <- fit$par
  post_var_matrix <- -solve(fit$hessian)
  p <- length(mode)
  int <- p/2 * log(2 * pi) + 0.5 * log(det(post_var_matrix)) + logpost_func(mode, ...)
  # package all of the results into a list
  list(mode = mode,
       var_matrix = post_var_matrix,
       log_evidence = int,
       converge = ifelse(fit$convergence == 0,
                         "YES", 
                         "NO"),
       iter_counts = as.numeric(fit$counts[1]))
}
laplace_3_weak<-my_laplace(start_guess=rep(0,ncol(Xmat_3_train)),logistic_logpost,info_3_weak)
laplace_3_strong<-my_laplace(start_guess=rep(0,ncol(Xmat_3_train)),logistic_logpost,info_3_strong)
laplace_2_weak<-my_laplace(start_guess=rep(0,ncol(Xmat_2_train)),logistic_logpost,info_2_weak)
laplace_2_strong<-my_laplace(start_guess=rep(0,ncol(Xmat_2_train)),logistic_logpost,info_2_strong)
summarize_logistic_pred_from_laplace <- function(mvn_result, Xtest, num_samples)
{
  # generate posterior samples of the beta parameters
  betas <- generate_glm_post_samples(mvn_result, num_samples)
  
  # data type conversion
  betas <- as.matrix(betas)
  
  # make posterior predictions on the test set
  pred_test <- post_logistic_pred_samples(Xtest, betas)
  
  # calculate summary statistics on the posterior predicted probability
  # summarize over the posterior samples
  
  # posterior mean, should you summarize along rows (rowMeans) or 
  # summarize down columns (colMeans) ???
  mu_avg <- rowMeans(pred_test$mu_mat)
  
  # posterior quantiles
  mu_q05 <- apply(pred_test$mu_mat, 1, stats::quantile, probs = 0.05)
  mu_q95 <- apply(pred_test$mu_mat, 1, stats::quantile, probs = 0.95)
  
  # book keeping
  tibble::tibble(
    mu_avg = mu_avg,
    mu_q05 = mu_q05,
    mu_q95 = mu_q95
  ) %>% 
    tibble::rowid_to_column("pred_id")
}
generate_glm_post_samples <- function(mvn_result, num_samples)
{
  # specify the number of unknown beta parameters
  length_beta <- length(mvn_result$mode)
  
  # generate the random samples
  beta_samples <- MASS::mvrnorm(n = num_samples, 
                                mu = mvn_result$mode, 
                                Sigma = mvn_result$var_matrix)
  
  # change the data type and name
  beta_samples %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
    purrr::set_names(sprintf("beta_%02d", (1:length_beta) - 1))
}
post_logistic_pred_samples <- function(Xnew, Bmat)
{
  # calculate the linear predictor at all prediction points and posterior samples
  eta_mat <- Xnew %*% t(Bmat)
  
  # calculate the event probability
  mu_mat <- boot::inv.logit(eta_mat)
  
  # book keeping
  list(eta_mat = eta_mat, mu_mat = mu_mat)
}

  bind_rows(post_pred_summary_2_strong_test_b%>%
              select(pred_class,outcome)%>%
              mutate(model_name='model_2_strong_test'))%>%
  group_by(model_name) %>% 
  summarise(num_correct = sum(pred_class == outcome),
            num_obs = n(),
            .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  mutate(Accuracy = num_correct / num_obs)
## # A tibble: 4  4
##   model_name          num_correct num_obs Accuracy
##   <chr>                     <int>   <int>    <dbl>
## 1 model_2_strong_test         169     204    0.828
## 2 model_3_strong_test         167     204    0.819
## 3 model2_weak_test            131     204    0.642
## 4 model3_weak_test            163     204    0.799

Based on the results above, model 3 is the best model based on Accuracy.
With the strong prior, model3 performs better in training set, but the performance of model 3 in test set is very close to model2. To prevent overfitting, we prefer to believe the result on test set.
With the weak prior, model3 performs much better than model2 in both weak and strong prior. To be honest, since in real situation we couldnt know the prior exactly, the result on weak prior seems to be much more precious than on strong prior.
Therefore, model3 is the best model.

##Visualize the regression coefficient posterior summary statistics for your best model.

viz_post_coefs <- function(post_means, post_sds, xnames)
{
  tibble::tibble(
    mu = post_means,
    sd = post_sds,
    x = xnames
  ) %>% 
    mutate(x = factor(x, levels = xnames)) %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = 'grey', linetype = 'dashed') +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(y = mu)) +
    geom_linerange(mapping = aes(ymin = mu - 2 * sd,
                                 ymax = mu + 2 * sd,
                                 group = x)) +
    labs(x = 'feature', y = 'coefficient value',cex=0.1) +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_bw()
}
viz_post_coefs(laplace_3_weak$mode[1:ncol(Xmat_3_train)],
               sqrt(diag(laplace_3_weak$var_matrix)[1:ncol(Xmat_3_train)]),colnames(Xmat_3_train))
